<!-- EXAM TIPS -->
<section id="tips">
<div class="page-wrap">
<div class="section-wrap tips-section" style="padding-top:0">

  <div class="section-header">
    <div>
      <div class="section-num">05</div>
      <div class="section-title-lg">Exam Tips<br><em>That Matter</em></div>
    </div>
    <div class="section-note">Not generic advice. These are the specific things that separate a 5 from a 6 in IB exams.</div>
  </div>

  <div class="tips-grid">
    <div class="tip-card"><div class="tip-num">01</div><div class="tip-title">Read the command term first</div><div class="tip-body">"Explain" ≠ "Evaluate" ≠ "Discuss." IB uses precise command terms. "Evaluate" always needs a judgment. Losing marks because you wrote the wrong type of answer is the most avoidable mistake.</div></div>
    <div class="tip-card"><div class="tip-num">02</div><div class="tip-title">Draw a diagram for every Econ answer</div><div class="tip-body">Even short 4-mark answers. A labelled diagram signals understanding immediately and earns marks even if your written explanation is incomplete. Never skip it.</div></div>
    <div class="tip-card"><div class="tip-num">03</div><div class="tip-title">The "however" rule</div><div class="tip-body">Any Business or Economics answer worth more than 4 marks needs evaluation. If your answer doesn't contain "however" or "on the other hand," you're probably missing evaluation marks.</div></div>
    <div class="tip-card"><div class="tip-num">04</div><div class="tip-title">Don't summarise the case study</div><div class="tip-body">In Business Paper 1, students waste time describing what the case study says. Marks are for applying business theory to the case study — not describing it back to the examiner.</div></div>
    <div class="tip-card"><div class="tip-num">05</div><div class="tip-title">Time management per paper</div><div class="tip-body">IB papers give roughly 1 minute per mark. A 10-mark question = 10 minutes. Stick to it — a blank question is always worse than an imperfect one written in the time you had left.</div></div>
    <div class="tip-card"><div class="tip-num">06</div><div class="tip-title">Past papers beat notes every time</div><div class="tip-body">Reading notes feels productive but isn't. 45 minutes attempting a past paper question + 15 minutes with the mark scheme is worth 3 hours of passive reading.</div></div>
    <div class="tip-card"><div class="tip-num">07</div><div class="tip-title">English: technique → effect always</div><div class="tip-body">"The writer uses a metaphor" = 0 marks. "The metaphor of machinery dehumanises the workers, positioning the reader to feel sympathy" = full marks. Always go one step further.</div></div>
    <div class="tip-card"><div class="tip-num">08</div><div class="tip-title">Sleep before the exam</div><div class="tip-body">Not negotiable. Sleep is when your brain consolidates memory. An all-nighter the day before actively makes you perform worse. The revision you did this week matters more if you sleep.</div></div>
    <div class="tip-card"><div class="tip-num">09</div><div class="tip-title">Answer every question</div><div class="tip-body">Blank answers score zero. A partial, uncertain answer can still earn 1–2 marks. In IB, those marks can move you across a grade boundary. Always write something.</div></div>
  </div>

</div>
</div>
</section>

